title: audio-session FIFO test asserts a wall-clock bound on a child process spawn (load-flaky)
updated_at: "2026-07-19T14:51:21Z"
---
OBSERVED: 'rejects an existing FIFO promptly without blocking on open' (code/repository/audio-session.test.ts:588) FAILED at 2132ms during a full pnpm check, then passed in isolation on the same commit.

CAUSE: the test spawns a child node process with --import tsx (a TypeScript transform on every run) and asserts:
  execFile(..., { timeout: 2_000 })
  expect(Date.now() - startedAt).toBeLessThan(2_000);
That is a wall-clock bound on process spawn plus TS transform. It is inherently sensitive to machine load, not to the behaviour under test. Under concurrent test suites it exceeds 2s and fails.

WHY IT MATTERS: the assertion's PURPOSE is to prove appendChunk rejects a FIFO promptly rather than blocking forever on open(). That is a real and worthwhile guarantee. But the current formulation conflates 'did not block indefinitely' with 'completed within 2s on a loaded machine', so it produces false failures that erode trust in the gate — and a gate people learn to re-run is a gate that stops catching things.

FIX OPTIONS (prefer 1):
1. Assert the OUTCOME, not the wall clock: the child must reject with a /regular file/ error. Keep execFile's timeout as the anti-hang backstop (a true block hits the timeout and fails), and drop the separate Date.now() assertion — the timeout already proves non-blocking.
2. If a timing bound is genuinely wanted, raise it substantially and precompile the child rather than transforming TS in-process, so it measures the open() behaviour instead of the toolchain.

Do NOT simply raise 2000 to a bigger number and leave the same shape; that defers the flake rather than fixing the conflation.